---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Standalone GNSS">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/positioning">Positioning</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>Standalone GNSS</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Positioning · Article 1 of 5</span>
        <h1>Standalone GNSS</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Standalone GNSS — also called single-point positioning or autonomous positioning — is what
          every phone, car and handheld GPS does by default. One receiver, no corrections, no reference
          station. Understanding its accuracy and limitations sets the baseline for every other
          positioning method.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>10 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#how-it-works">How it works</a></li>
          <li><a href="#navigation-solution">The navigation solution</a></li>
          <li><a href="#accuracy">Accuracy and error budget</a></li>
          <li><a href="#sps">GPS Standard Positioning Service</a></li>
          <li><a href="#dual-frequency-benefit">The dual-frequency benefit</a></li>
          <li><a href="#when-to-use">When standalone is sufficient</a></li>
          <li><a href="#limitations">Fundamental limitations</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="how-it-works">How it works</h2>
      <p>
        A standalone receiver does everything itself. It acquires signals from visible satellites,
        measures pseudoranges, decodes navigation messages, computes satellite positions from
        ephemeris, and solves for its own position and clock offset — all with no external input.
      </p>
      <p>
        The only data entering the system are the satellite signals themselves. The receiver has no
        knowledge of nearby reference stations, no correction data stream and no prior position
        information (in cold-start mode). This self-contained nature is both standalone's greatest
        strength (works anywhere with sky view) and its greatest weakness (all errors must be
        modelled or tolerated).
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="navigation-solution">The navigation solution</h2>
      <p>
        With n ≥ 4 satellites, the receiver solves the following system of pseudorange equations
        simultaneously for position (x, y, z) and receiver clock offset δt:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">ρ_i = √[(x − x_i)² + (y − y_i)² + (z − z_i)²] + c·δt + ε_i</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          For each satellite i: ρ_i = measured pseudorange (m), (x_i, y_i, z_i) = satellite position
          from ephemeris (m), c = speed of light (m/s), δt = receiver clock offset (s),
          ε_i = residual error from all sources (m).
          The system has 4 unknowns: x, y, z, δt.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        This system is non-linear — the unknowns appear inside square roots. The standard approach
        is to linearise around an approximate position (x₀, y₀, z₀) and solve iteratively
        using the least squares method:
      </p>

      <ol class="steps">
        <li><strong>Initial guess:</strong> Start with an approximate position — typically the last known position or the centre of the Earth for a cold start.</li>
        <li><strong>Linearise:</strong> Compute the Jacobian (design matrix H) of partial derivatives at the current estimate.</li>
        <li><strong>Least squares update:</strong> Δx = (HᵀH)⁻¹Hᵀ·Δρ, where Δρ is the vector of pseudorange residuals.</li>
        <li><strong>Update estimate:</strong> Add Δx to the current position estimate.</li>
        <li><strong>Repeat:</strong> Continue until convergence — typically 3–5 iterations from a reasonable starting point.</li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        With more than 4 satellites (the usual case — modern receivers track 10–40 simultaneously),
        the system is <strong>overdetermined</strong>. Least squares finds the position that minimises
        the sum of squared pseudorange residuals, giving better accuracy and enabling integrity checks.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">📊</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Weighted least squares:</strong> In practice, pseudoranges from different satellites
          are not equally reliable. Low-elevation satellites have higher noise and more tropospheric
          delay. Quality receivers use <strong>weighted least squares</strong>, assigning lower weight
          to low-elevation and low-SNR observations. The weight matrix W is typically diagonal with
          elements proportional to sin²(elevation).
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="accuracy">Accuracy and error budget</h2>
      <p>
        Standalone accuracy is the product of two independent factors:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">σ_position = DOP × σ_UERE</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          DOP depends on satellite geometry (see the <a href="/learn/fundamentals/dilution-of-precision">DOP article</a>).
          σ_UERE is the combined 1σ ranging error from all sources. For GPS SPS (single-frequency L1),
          the broadcast specification guarantees σ_UERE ≤ 4 m (SIS URE).
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The major contributors to σ_UERE in a standalone receiver are:
      </p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Error source</th>
              <th>Single-freq (1σ)</th>
              <th>Dual-freq (1σ)</th>
              <th>Notes</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Ionospheric delay</td>
              <td>~3.0 m</td>
              <td>&lt;0.1 m</td>
              <td>Largest single-frequency error. Klobuchar model reduces by ~50%.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Tropospheric delay</td>
              <td>~0.5 m</td>
              <td>~0.5 m</td>
              <td>Not frequency-dependent. Saastamoinen model gives ~0.1 m residual.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Satellite clock</td>
              <td>~0.5 m</td>
              <td>~0.5 m</td>
              <td>After applying broadcast clock correction. Spec is ≤1 m (SIS URE).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Ephemeris error</td>
              <td>~0.5 m</td>
              <td>~0.5 m</td>
              <td>Radial component after applying broadcast ephemeris correction.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Multipath</td>
              <td>~1.0 m</td>
              <td>~0.5 m</td>
              <td>Environment-dependent. Open-sky typically &lt;0.5 m. Urban up to 10 m.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Receiver noise</td>
              <td>~0.3 m</td>
              <td>~0.3 m</td>
              <td>Depends on receiver quality. Consumer: 0.3–0.5 m. Survey: 0.1–0.3 m.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="font-weight:600;">
              <td><strong>Total σ_UERE</strong></td>
              <td><strong>~3.5 m</strong></td>
              <td><strong>~1.0 m</strong></td>
              <td>RSS combination of above. With DOP = 1.5: 5 m / 1.5 m position error.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="sps">GPS Standard Positioning Service</h2>
      <p>
        The GPS Standard Positioning Service (SPS) is the freely available civil positioning service.
        It is defined in the <strong>GPS SPS Performance Standard</strong>, which specifies guaranteed
        accuracy levels for L1 C/A code receivers anywhere in the world:
      </p>

      <div class="spec-grid">
        <div class="spec-card">
          <div class="spec-value">≤ 9 m</div>
          <div class="spec-label">Horizontal (95%)</div>
          <div class="spec-note">Global average. Includes all error sources.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="spec-card">
          <div class="spec-value">≤ 15 m</div>
          <div class="spec-label">Vertical (95%)</div>
          <div class="spec-note">Vertical is always weaker — higher VDOP.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="spec-card">
          <div class="spec-value">≤ 40 ns</div>
          <div class="spec-label">UTC timing (95%)</div>
          <div class="spec-note">After applying broadcast corrections.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="spec-card">
          <div class="spec-value">≥ 95%</div>
          <div class="spec-label">Availability</div>
          <div class="spec-note">Probability of 4+ satellites with PDOP ≤ 6.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        In practice, modern multi-constellation receivers significantly outperform these GPS-only
        specifications. A typical smartphone with GPS+Galileo+BeiDou in open sky achieves
        2–4 m horizontal (95%) — well below the GPS SPS guarantee.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">📜</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Selective Availability:</strong> Until May 2000, the US intentionally degraded
          GPS accuracy for civilian users (Selective Availability, SA) to ~100 m horizontal.
          SA was permanently discontinued by presidential order. The GPS SPS Performance Standard
          now guarantees no intentional degradation for civil use.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="dual-frequency-benefit">The dual-frequency benefit</h2>
      <p>
        The biggest single improvement available to a standalone receiver is moving from
        single-frequency to dual-frequency. The ionosphere — the dominant error source —
        is eliminated by the ionosphere-free combination:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">ρ_IF = (f₁² · ρ₁ − f₂² · ρ₂) / (f₁² − f₂²)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          For GPS L1/L5: f₁ = 1575.42 MHz, f₂ = 1176.45 MHz. The combined pseudorange ρ_IF
          has ionospheric delay removed to first order (~99.9%). Residual second-order
          ionospheric effects are typically &lt;1 cm.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The trade-off is amplified noise. The ionosphere-free combination amplifies measurement noise
        by a factor of:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">noise_IF = √(f₁⁴ + f₂⁴) / |f₁² − f₂²| × noise_single</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          For GPS L1/L5: amplification factor ≈ 2.6×. So if individual pseudorange noise is 0.3 m,
          the ionosphere-free combination noise is ~0.8 m. This is still much better than the 3+ m
          ionospheric error it removes.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="before-after">
        <div class="ba-col">
          <div class="ba-title">Single-frequency L1</div>
          <div class="ba-items">
            <div class="ba-item bad">Ionosphere: 3–10 m</div>
            <div class="ba-item neutral">Troposphere: ~0.5 m</div>
            <div class="ba-item neutral">Clocks + ephemeris: ~1 m</div>
            <div class="ba-item neutral">Multipath: ~1 m</div>
            <div class="ba-item neutral">Noise: ~0.3 m</div>
          </div>
          <div class="ba-result">Typical accuracy: 3–5 m</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ba-arrow">→</div>
        <div class="ba-col">
          <div class="ba-title">Dual-frequency L1+L5</div>
          <div class="ba-items">
            <div class="ba-item good">Ionosphere: &lt;0.1 m ✓</div>
            <div class="ba-item neutral">Troposphere: ~0.5 m</div>
            <div class="ba-item neutral">Clocks + ephemeris: ~1 m</div>
            <div class="ba-item neutral">Multipath: ~0.5 m</div>
            <div class="ba-item bad">IF noise: ~0.8 m (amplified)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="ba-result">Typical accuracy: 1–2 m</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="when-to-use">When standalone is sufficient</h2>
      <p>
        Standalone GNSS at 2–5 m accuracy is appropriate for a wide range of applications:
      </p>

      <div class="use-case-grid">
        <div class="use-case use-yes">
          <div class="use-icon">✅</div>
          <div class="use-title">Good fit</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Turn-by-turn navigation (cars, phones)</li>
            <li>Fleet tracking and logistics</li>
            <li>Asset tracking (&gt;5 m accuracy adequate)</li>
            <li>Outdoor recreation (hiking, cycling)</li>
            <li>General mapping and GIS data collection</li>
            <li>Emergency response dispatch</li>
            <li>Precision agriculture (field-level, not in-row)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="use-case use-no">
          <div class="use-icon">❌</div>
          <div class="use-title">Needs better accuracy</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Lane-level autonomous driving (&lt;0.5 m needed)</li>
            <li>Land survey and cadastral mapping (&lt;0.1 m)</li>
            <li>Machine control — grading, paving, drilling</li>
            <li>Structural deformation monitoring</li>
            <li>UAV precision landing and inspection</li>
            <li>RTK agriculture — in-row guidance</li>
            <li>Hydrographic survey</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="limitations">Fundamental limitations</h2>
      <p>
        Even with ideal hardware, perfect satellite geometry and a clear sky, standalone GNSS has
        hard accuracy limits that cannot be overcome without external corrections:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Broadcast ephemeris accuracy:</strong> ~0.5–1 m radial orbit error is inherent in
          the broadcast navigation message. Overcoming this requires precise ephemeris from IGS or
          a real-time correction service — impossible standalone.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Broadcast clock accuracy:</strong> ~0.5 m equivalent range error. Again, requires
          precise clock corrections to improve.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Tropospheric wet component:</strong> The unpredictable wet troposphere contributes
          ~0.1–0.3 m residual after modelling. Cannot be eliminated without external water vapour
          measurements.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Code measurement noise:</strong> Code phase measurement noise (~0.1–0.5 m) sets a
          floor on standalone accuracy. Carrier phase is 100× more precise but requires ambiguity
          resolution — which needs either a base station (RTK) or precise products (PPP).
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔑</div>
        <div>
          <strong>The key insight:</strong> Going from standalone (~3 m) to RTK (~2 cm) is not an
          incremental improvement — it requires a fundamentally different measurement type (carrier
          phase instead of code) and a completely different processing approach (differential, with
          integer ambiguity resolution). The next articles in this section explain how.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📍</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Code-based positioning</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Standalone uses pseudorange (code) measurements. Noise ~0.3 m per satellite, but systematic errors (iono, tropo, clocks) dominate — total UERE ~3.5 m.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🛰️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">4 unknowns, 4 equations</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Solve for (x, y, z, δt) simultaneously. Overdetermined with ≥5 satellites — use weighted least squares for better accuracy and integrity.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📶</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Dual-frequency improves standalone</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Eliminating the ionospheric delay cuts standalone UERE from ~3.5 m to ~1 m. Most modern smartphones are dual-frequency.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🚧</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Hard accuracy floor</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Broadcast clock/ephemeris errors (~1 m combined) and tropospheric wet component (~0.2 m) set a practical floor of ~1–2 m for standalone dual-frequency.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/positioning" class="nav-prev">← Positioning</a>
        <a href="/learn/positioning/dgnss-and-sbas" class="nav-next">DGNSS and SBAS →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>GPS SPS Performance Standard, 5th Edition (2020). <a href="https://www.gps.gov/technical/ps/2020-SPS-performance-standard.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GPS.gov →</a></li>
          <li>Kaplan, E. D. & Hegarty, C. J. (2017). <em>Understanding GPS/GNSS: Principles and Applications</em>, 3rd ed. Artech House. Chapter 7.</li>
          <li>Misra, P. & Enge, P. (2011). <em>Global Positioning System: Signals, Measurements and Performance</em>, 2nd ed. Ganga-Jamuna Press. Chapter 5.</li>
          <li>IS-GPS-200N. <a href="https://www.navcen.uscg.gov/sites/default/files/pdf/gps/IS-GPS-200N.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NAVCEN →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learn-container { max-width: 820px; }
  .breadcrumb { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--text2); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(24px, 4vw, 38px); font-weight: 700; margin: 10px 0 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
  h2 { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; margin: 40px 0 16px; padding-top: 8px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .lead { font-size: 17px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 12px; max-width: 720px; }
  .article-meta { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); display: flex; gap: 8px; }
  p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  ul { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; padding-left: 24px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  li { margin-bottom: 8px; }
  strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }
  a { color: var(--accent2); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }

  .toc { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px 24px; margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .toc-title { font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .toc ol { margin: 0; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .toc li { font-size: 14px; }
  .toc a { color: var(--text2); text-decoration: none; }
  .toc a:hover { color: var(--accent); }

  .callout { display: flex; gap: 14px; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 24px 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; }
  .callout-icon { font-size: 18px; flex-shrink: 0; }
  .callout-info { background: rgba(0,153,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(0,153,255,0.18); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout strong { color: var(--text); }

  .formula-block { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-left: 3px solid var(--accent); border-radius: 8px; padding: 18px 20px; margin: 20px 0; overflow-x: auto; }
  .formula { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 14px; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 4px; line-height: 1.7; }
  .formula-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.6; margin-top: 8px; }

  .steps { counter-reset: step; list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 16px 0; }
  .steps li { counter-increment: step; padding: 12px 12px 12px 48px; position: relative; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-size: 14px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.7; }
  .steps li:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .steps li::before { content: counter(step); position: absolute; left: 12px; top: 14px; width: 22px; height: 22px; background: rgba(0,212,170,0.12); color: var(--accent); border-radius: 50%; font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-family: var(--mono); }

  .table-wrap { overflow-x: auto; margin: 20px 0; }
  table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 13px; }
  thead tr { background: var(--bg3); }
  th { padding: 10px 12px; text-align: left; font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); }
  td { padding: 10px 12px; color: var(--text2); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); vertical-align: top; }
  tr:last-child td { border-bottom: none; }
  tr:hover td { background: var(--bg3); }

  /* Spec grid */
  .spec-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr); gap: 12px; margin: 20px 0; }
  .spec-card { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 16px; text-align: center; }
  .spec-value { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .spec-label { font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 4px; }
  .spec-note { font-size: 11px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.5; }

  /* Before/after */
  .before-after { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr auto 1fr; gap: 12px; align-items: center; margin: 20px 0; }
  .ba-col { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 16px; }
  .ba-title { font-size: 13px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .ba-items { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 4px; margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .ba-item { font-size: 12px; padding: 4px 8px; border-radius: 4px; font-family: var(--mono); }
  .ba-item.bad { background: rgba(255,71,87,0.1); color: #ff4757; }
  .ba-item.good { background: rgba(0,212,170,0.1); color: var(--accent); }
  .ba-item.neutral { background: var(--bg3); color: var(--text3); }
  .ba-result { font-size: 13px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); padding-top: 8px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .ba-arrow { font-size: 24px; color: var(--accent); text-align: center; }

  /* Use case grid */
  .use-case-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 14px; margin: 16px 0; }
  .use-case { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 18px; }
  .use-icon { font-size: 20px; margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .use-title { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .use-case ul { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); padding-left: 18px; margin: 0; }
  .use-case li { margin-bottom: 4px; }
  .use-yes { border-color: rgba(0,212,170,0.2); }
  .use-no { border-color: rgba(255,71,87,0.2); }

  .summary-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); gap: 14px; margin: 24px 0; }
  .summary-card { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px; }
  .summary-icon { font-size: 22px; margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .summary-title { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .summary-body { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); line-height: 1.6; }

  .nav-footer { display: flex; justify-content: space-between; margin: 48px 0 32px; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 12px; }
